The nematodes were extracted by sieving and decantation followed by the Baermann funnel technique (
Flegg, 1967
). Extracted nematodes were fixed in formaldehyde-glycerin fixative (
Hooper, 1970
) for 24 hrs and then trans- ferred to glycerine-alcohol (5 parts glycerin: 95 parts 30% alcohol, 
Seinhorst, 1959
) for slow dehydration in a desiccator. Dehydrated specimens were mounted in anhydrous glycerin on glass slides using the wax ring method (
De Maeseneer & d’Herde, 1963
). All observations, drawings, and photographs were made on an Olympus BX 50 DIC microscope. For scanning electron microscopy, fixed specimens were processed in a glycerin: absolute ethanol graded series (% glycerin in absolute ethanol: 70, 50, 30 and 0). The last step was repeated twice to ensure that the glycerin was completely exchanged with ethanol and then specimens were transferred to distilled water. After rehydration, specimens were fixed in 3% glutaraldehyde in 0.05 M phosphate buffer (
Kiontke, Manegold & Sudhaus, 2001
) for 48 hrs, washed in 0.05 M sodium phosphate buffer (pH=6.9) several times, dehydrated in a graded ethanol series and critical–point dried in carbon dioxide (
Eisenback, 1985
). Dried specimens were mounted on stubs, coated with gold and observed in a Joel JSM 6510 LV at 15 KV.
